digraph BuildExtension {
    label="Build Bookmark Board Chrome Extension"
    goal="Build a Toby-like bookmark manager as a Chrome extension with three-panel layout, bookmark import, open tabs sidebar, and drag-and-drop."
    model="sonnet"

    start [shape="Mdiamond", label="Start"]
    done  [shape="Msquare",  label="Done"]

    // ─── Phase 1: Foundation ───────────────────────────────────

    investigate_structure [
        shape="box"
        label="Investigate Chrome MV3"
        allowed_tools="Read,Grep,Glob,WebFetch,WebSearch"
        prompt="Research Chrome Manifest V3 extension structure for a new-tab override extension. Document:
1. Required manifest.json fields for permissions: bookmarks, tabs, storage, favicon
2. How chrome_url_overrides works for newtab
3. How to use the /_favicon/ API (chrome://favicon/ replacement in MV3)
4. chrome.storage.local API usage patterns
5. chrome.bookmarks.getSubTree API for reading Bookmark Bar (node ID '1')
6. chrome.tabs query/event listener APIs

Write findings to .attractor/mv3-research.md"
    ]

    scaffold [
        shape="box"
        label="Create Extension Scaffold"
        prompt="Read .attractor/mv3-research.md for context.

Create the Chrome extension scaffold in /Volumes/qwiizlab/projects/bookmark_board/:

1. manifest.json — Manifest V3 with:
   - name: 'Bookmark Board'
   - permissions: ['bookmarks', 'tabs', 'storage']
   - chrome_url_overrides: { newtab: 'newtab.html' }
   - icons: reference icons/icon16.png, icon48.png, icon128.png

2. newtab.html — Shell HTML with three-panel CSS grid:
   - Left sidebar (spaces nav, 240px)
   - Main area (collections grid, flexible)
   - Right sidebar (open tabs, 280px)
   - Link to newtab.css and all JS modules

3. newtab.css — Complete styles for:
   - Three-panel grid layout (100vh, no scroll on body)
   - Left sidebar: dark bg, space list items, active state
   - Main area: light bg, collection cards as sections, bookmark cards with large favicons
   - Right sidebar: tab entries grouped by window
   - Bookmark card: 32px favicon, title, subtle URL on hover, rounded corners, shadow
   - Collection: header with name + collapse toggle, card grid inside
   - Scrollable panels independently
   - Clean modern look inspired by Toby (teal/dark sidebar, white main area)

4. js/utils.js — Helper functions:
   - uid() — generate random IDs like 'sp_abc123'
   - faviconUrl(pageUrl) — return chrome-extension favicon URL using /_favicon/?pageUrl=URL&size=32
   - debounce(fn, ms)

5. icons/ — Create simple colored SVG-based PNG placeholders (or use a single-color square as placeholder). Create icon16.png, icon48.png, icon128.png.

6. newtab.js — Empty entry point that will import other modules.

Use port 0 (no server needed — this is a chrome extension loaded from disk).
Do NOT use ES module imports — use plain script tags in order in newtab.html since MV3 content security policy can be restrictive. All JS files should add to a global BookmarkBoard namespace."
    ]

    verify_scaffold [
        shape="diamond"
        label="Verify Scaffold"
        node_type="conditional"
        prompt="Read the following files and verify they exist and are well-formed:
- /Volumes/qwiizlab/projects/bookmark_board/manifest.json (valid JSON, has correct permissions)
- /Volumes/qwiizlab/projects/bookmark_board/newtab.html (references CSS and all JS files)
- /Volumes/qwiizlab/projects/bookmark_board/newtab.css (has three-panel grid, bookmark card styles)
- /Volumes/qwiizlab/projects/bookmark_board/js/utils.js (has uid, faviconUrl, debounce functions)

Check that:
1. manifest.json is valid MV3 with bookmarks+tabs+storage permissions
2. newtab.html loads CSS and JS in correct order (utils.js first)
3. CSS has a proper three-column grid layout
4. All files reference a shared BookmarkBoard namespace (not ES modules)

Respond PASS or FAIL on the last line."
    ]

    fix_scaffold [
        shape="box"
        label="Fix Scaffold Issues"
        prompt="Read .attractor/scaffold-issues.md and fix the problems identified in the scaffold verification step. Re-read each file after fixing to confirm."
        retry_target="verify_scaffold"
    ]

    // ─── Phase 2: Data Store ───────────────────────────────────

    build_store [
        shape="box"
        label="Build Data Store"
        prompt="Create /Volumes/qwiizlab/projects/bookmark_board/js/store.js

This is the data persistence layer using chrome.storage.local. Add to the BookmarkBoard namespace.

Data model:
- spaces: [{ id, name, order, collectionIds }]
- collections: [{ id, spaceId, name, tags, order, collapsed, bookmarks }]
- bookmarks (inside collections): [{ id, title, url, order }]
- tags: string[]
- settings: { theme: 'light' }

Implement these async functions on BookmarkBoard.Store:

Space CRUD:
- init() — load all data from storage; if empty, seed with default space 'My Collections'
- getSpaces() — return all spaces sorted by order
- addSpace(name) — create space, return it
- renameSpace(id, name)
- removeSpace(id) — also remove its collections
- reorderSpaces(orderedIds)

Collection CRUD:
- getCollections(spaceId) — return collections for a space, sorted by order
- addCollection(spaceId, name) — create collection, return it
- renameCollection(id, name)
- removeCollection(id) — also update parent space
- toggleCollapse(id)
- reorderCollections(spaceId, orderedIds)
- setCollectionTags(id, tags)

Bookmark CRUD:
- addBookmark(collectionId, { title, url }) — add to end, return bookmark
- removeBookmark(collectionId, bookmarkId)
- moveBookmark(fromCollectionId, toCollectionId, bookmarkId, newIndex)
- reorderBookmarks(collectionId, orderedIds)

Tag CRUD:
- getTags()
- addTag(name)
- removeTag(name)

Internal:
- _save() — persist entire state to chrome.storage.local
- _load() — read from chrome.storage.local

All functions should be async. Use a single _save() call pattern — load full state into memory, mutate, then save back. This avoids race conditions."
    ]

    // ─── Phase 3: Rendering ───────────────────────────────────

    build_render [
        shape="box"
        label="Build Renderer"
        prompt="Create /Volumes/qwiizlab/projects/bookmark_board/js/render.js

This renders the entire UI. Add to BookmarkBoard.Render namespace. It should read from BookmarkBoard.Store and update the DOM.

Implement:

1. renderSidebar() — Left panel:
   - List all spaces with click handler to switch active space
   - Active space highlighted with teal/accent color
   - Each space has a 3-dot menu (rename, delete)
   - '+ Add Space' button at bottom
   - Use icons/emoji for visual interest (folder icon before space names)

2. renderCollections(spaceId) — Main panel:
   - Clear main area, render all collections for the active space
   - Each collection is a section with:
     - Header: collection name (editable on double-click), collapse/expand chevron, tag chips, 3-dot menu (rename, delete, add tags, open all tabs)
     - Body: grid of bookmark cards (3-4 columns, responsive)
   - Each bookmark card:
     - Large favicon (32px) using BookmarkBoard.faviconUrl()
     - Title text (truncated if long)
     - URL shown subtly below or on hover
     - Click opens URL in new tab
     - Small X button to remove (visible on hover)
   - '+ Add Collection' button at top
   - If collection is collapsed, hide bookmark body

3. renderTagBar() — Top of main area:
   - Show all tags as clickable filter chips
   - Active tag filter highlights the chip and hides non-matching collections
   - 'Clear filter' option

4. renderSearch() — Search input in top bar:
   - On input, filter visible bookmarks across all collections by title/URL match
   - Debounced (300ms)

5. renderAll() — Orchestrator that calls all render functions

6. Event delegation — Use event delegation on the three panels rather than per-element listeners.

Also update newtab.js to:
- Call BookmarkBoard.Store.init() on DOMContentLoaded
- Then call BookmarkBoard.Render.renderAll()
- Set up the active space (first space by default)

Make sure newtab.html loads scripts in order: utils.js, store.js, render.js, then newtab.js last."
    ]

    verify_render [
        shape="diamond"
        label="Verify Core UI"
        node_type="conditional"
        prompt="Read all files in /Volumes/qwiizlab/projects/bookmark_board/ and verify:

1. newtab.html loads scripts in correct order: utils.js, store.js, render.js, newtab.js
2. js/store.js has all CRUD functions and seeds default data on init()
3. js/render.js renders sidebar, collections, bookmark cards, tag bar, and search
4. newtab.js initializes store and triggers first render
5. newtab.css has styles for all rendered elements (bookmark cards, collection headers, sidebar items, tag chips)
6. Event handlers are wired up (space click, collection actions, bookmark click/remove, search input)
7. No ES module import/export syntax used (all via BookmarkBoard namespace)

Respond PASS or FAIL on the last line."
    ]

    fix_render [
        shape="box"
        label="Fix Render Issues"
        prompt="Read .attractor/render-issues.md and fix all problems found during render verification. Check each file after fixing."
        retry_target="verify_render"
    ]

    // ─── Phase 4: Import ──────────────────────────────────────

    build_import [
        shape="box"
        label="Build Bookmark Import"
        prompt="Create /Volumes/qwiizlab/projects/bookmark_board/js/import.js

Add to BookmarkBoard.Import namespace. This handles importing Chrome bookmarks into the app.

Implement:

1. importBookmarkBar() — Main import function:
   - Use chrome.bookmarks.getSubTree('1') to get the Bookmark Bar tree
   - For each FOLDER in the bookmark bar: create a Collection with the folder's name
   - For each bookmark inside a folder: add as a bookmark in that collection
   - For loose bookmarks (directly in bookmark bar, not in a folder): add to an 'Unsorted' collection
   - Handle nested folders: flatten them (subfolder becomes its own collection, prefixed with parent name e.g. 'Dev > Tools')
   - Skip duplicates: if a bookmark URL already exists in the target collection, skip it
   - Add all new collections to the active space

2. showImportModal() — UI for import:
   - Show a modal/overlay with 'Import from Bookmark Bar' button
   - Show progress: 'Importing... X bookmarks found'
   - Show summary when done: 'Imported X collections with Y bookmarks'
   - Close button

3. Auto-import on first run:
   - In BookmarkBoard.Store.init(), check for a 'hasImported' flag in settings
   - If false, trigger showImportModal() after initial render
   - Set 'hasImported' = true after successful import

4. Manual re-import:
   - Add an 'Import Bookmarks' option accessible from the UI (gear icon or menu)
   - Incremental: only adds new bookmarks, doesn't duplicate existing URLs

Update newtab.html to include import.js in the script loading order (after render.js, before newtab.js).
Update newtab.js to check for first-run import after init."
    ]

    // ─── Phase 5: Open Tabs ──────────────────────────────────

    build_tabs [
        shape="box"
        label="Build Open Tabs Sidebar"
        prompt="Create /Volumes/qwiizlab/projects/bookmark_board/js/tabs.js

Add to BookmarkBoard.Tabs namespace. This manages the right sidebar showing open browser tabs.

Implement:

1. loadTabs() — Query and render:
   - Use chrome.tabs.query({}) to get all tabs
   - Group tabs by windowId
   - Sort windows by windowId (label as 'Window 1', 'Window 2', etc.)
   - Render in right sidebar panel:
     - Window header with collapse/expand toggle
     - Each tab: favicon (16px), truncated title, small X to close tab
     - Current tab highlighted
   - Each tab entry should be draggable (for drag-and-drop into collections)

2. setupListeners() — Live updates:
   - chrome.tabs.onCreated → add tab to correct window group
   - chrome.tabs.onRemoved → remove tab entry
   - chrome.tabs.onUpdated → update title/favicon if changed
   - chrome.tabs.onMoved → update order
   - chrome.windows.onCreated → add new window group
   - chrome.windows.onRemoved → remove window group
   - Debounce re-renders to avoid flicker

3. Tab actions:
   - Click tab entry → chrome.tabs.update(tabId, {active:true}) + chrome.windows.update(windowId, {focused:true})
   - Click X on tab → chrome.tabs.remove(tabId)
   - 'Save Session' button per window → creates new collection from all tabs in that window using BookmarkBoard.Store.addCollection() and addBookmark()

4. Exclude the new tab page itself from the tab list (filter out chrome://newtab and extension URLs).

Update newtab.html to include tabs.js in script loading order.
Update newtab.js to call BookmarkBoard.Tabs.loadTabs() and BookmarkBoard.Tabs.setupListeners() after store init."
    ]

    // ─── Phase 6: Drag & Drop ─────────────────────────────────

    build_dragdrop [
        shape="box"
        label="Build Drag & Drop"
        prompt="Create /Volumes/qwiizlab/projects/bookmark_board/js/dragdrop.js

Add to BookmarkBoard.DragDrop namespace. Uses native HTML5 Drag and Drop API (no libraries).

Implement:

1. init() — Set up drag and drop:
   - Make bookmark cards draggable (set draggable='true' in render.js)
   - Make open tab entries draggable
   - Set up drop zones on collection bodies and collection headers

2. Drag sources — attach dragstart/dragend handlers:
   - Bookmark cards: set dataTransfer with type='bookmark', collectionId, bookmarkId
   - Open tab entries: set dataTransfer with type='tab', tabId, title, url
   - Add a 'dragging' CSS class for visual feedback (opacity reduction)

3. Drop targets — attach dragover/dragenter/dragleave/drop handlers:
   - Collection body: accepts bookmarks and tabs
   - On dragover: add 'drop-target' CSS class (highlight border/background)
   - On dragleave: remove highlight
   - On drop:
     a. If type='bookmark': call BookmarkBoard.Store.moveBookmark() then re-render
     b. If type='tab': call BookmarkBoard.Store.addBookmark() with tab's title+url, then re-render

4. Reordering within a collection:
   - Track drop position relative to existing bookmark cards
   - Insert at the correct index using reorderBookmarks()

5. CSS classes to add to newtab.css:
   - .dragging { opacity: 0.4; }
   - .drop-target { border: 2px dashed #4db6ac; background: rgba(77,182,172,0.05); }
   - .drag-ghost { ... } (optional custom drag image)

Update newtab.html to include dragdrop.js in script loading order.
Update newtab.js to call BookmarkBoard.DragDrop.init() after render.
Update js/render.js to set draggable='true' on bookmark cards and tab entries."
    ]

    verify_full [
        shape="diamond"
        label="Verify Full Build"
        node_type="conditional"
        goal_gate="true"
        retry_target="fix_full"
        prompt="Do a comprehensive review of all files in /Volumes/qwiizlab/projects/bookmark_board/.

Verify:
1. manifest.json is valid MV3, has all required permissions
2. newtab.html loads all 7 JS files in correct dependency order: utils.js, store.js, render.js, import.js, tabs.js, dragdrop.js, newtab.js
3. All JS files use BookmarkBoard namespace consistently (no ES modules)
4. Store has complete CRUD for spaces, collections, bookmarks, tags
5. Render creates the full three-panel UI with sidebar, collections grid, and tabs sidebar
6. Import reads from chrome.bookmarks API and maps folders to collections
7. Tabs sidebar queries chrome.tabs and sets up live listeners
8. Drag and drop works for both bookmark reordering and tab-to-collection drops
9. CSS covers all UI elements: sidebar, collection headers, bookmark cards, tab entries, modals, drag states
10. No obvious bugs: undefined references, missing function calls, broken event handlers
11. newtab.js properly orchestrates initialization in the right order

Respond PASS or FAIL on the last line. If FAIL, write specific issues to .attractor/full-build-issues.md"
    ]

    fix_full [
        shape="box"
        label="Fix Full Build Issues"
        prompt="Read .attractor/full-build-issues.md and fix ALL issues found. This is the final quality gate — make sure everything works together:
- All cross-file references resolve correctly
- Event handlers are properly wired
- CSS classes match what JS adds/removes
- chrome.* API calls use correct signatures
- No missing script tags in newtab.html

Re-read every file after fixing to confirm."
        retry_target="verify_full"
    ]

    // ─── Phase 7: AI Grouping (Enhancement) ───────────────────

    build_ai_grouping [
        shape="box"
        label="Build AI Grouping"
        prompt="Add AI-powered bookmark organization to /Volumes/qwiizlab/projects/bookmark_board/.

Create js/ai-grouping.js (add to BookmarkBoard.AI namespace):

1. showSettingsModal() — Settings UI:
   - Modal with API key input field (for Anthropic/OpenAI API)
   - Model selector dropdown
   - Save to chrome.storage.local under settings.aiApiKey and settings.aiModel
   - Test connection button

2. organizeWithAI(bookmarks) — Main function:
   - Takes an array of bookmarks [{title, url}]
   - Sends to LLM API with a prompt like:
     'Given these bookmarks, suggest collection groupings. Return JSON: { collections: [{ name: string, bookmarkIndices: number[] }] }'
   - Parse response and return suggested groupings

3. showOrganizeModal() — UI flow:
   - Collect all bookmarks from 'Unsorted' collection or selected collections
   - Show 'Organizing with AI...' spinner
   - Call organizeWithAI()
   - Show preview: proposed collection names with bookmarks listed under each
   - 'Apply' button to create the collections and move bookmarks
   - 'Cancel' to discard suggestions

4. Add 'Organize with AI' button:
   - Visible in the top bar or as a menu option
   - Only enabled if API key is configured

Update newtab.html to include ai-grouping.js.
Update newtab.css with modal styles for settings and organize preview."
    ]

    // ─── Phase 8: Polish ──────────────────────────────────────

    polish [
        shape="box"
        label="Polish & UX"
        prompt="Final polish pass on /Volumes/qwiizlab/projects/bookmark_board/.

Add these finishing touches:

1. Context menus — Right-click on bookmark card:
   - Edit title (inline edit)
   - Copy URL to clipboard
   - Open in new tab
   - Open in new window
   - Delete

2. Collection actions — 3-dot menu on collection header:
   - Open all tabs (opens all bookmarks in new window)
   - Rename collection
   - Add/edit tags
   - Delete collection (with confirmation)

3. Keyboard shortcuts:
   - '/' focuses the search input
   - 'Escape' clears search and closes modals

4. Dark mode:
   - Add a theme toggle button (sun/moon icon) in the top bar
   - Add CSS custom properties for colors (--bg-primary, --bg-secondary, --text-primary, etc.)
   - Dark theme class on body swaps the custom properties
   - Save preference in settings

5. Empty states:
   - No collections yet → show 'Import your bookmarks to get started' with import button
   - Empty collection → show 'Drag tabs here or add bookmarks' placeholder
   - No search results → show 'No bookmarks match your search'

6. Visual refinements:
   - Smooth transitions on collapse/expand (max-height animation)
   - Hover effects on cards (subtle lift/shadow)
   - Loading state on initial render
   - Favicon fallback for broken/missing favicons (show first letter of domain)

7. Update PIPELINE.md — Mark all steps as [x] done."
    ]

    // ─── Edges ────────────────────────────────────────────────

    start -> investigate_structure
    investigate_structure -> scaffold
    scaffold -> verify_scaffold

    verify_scaffold -> build_store       [label="PASS", condition="preferred_label=PASS"]
    verify_scaffold -> fix_scaffold      [label="FAIL", condition="preferred_label=FAIL"]

    build_store -> build_render
    build_render -> verify_render

    verify_render -> build_import        [label="PASS", condition="preferred_label=PASS"]
    verify_render -> fix_render          [label="FAIL", condition="preferred_label=FAIL"]

    build_import -> build_tabs
    build_tabs -> build_dragdrop
    build_dragdrop -> verify_full

    verify_full -> build_ai_grouping     [label="PASS", condition="preferred_label=PASS"]
    verify_full -> fix_full              [label="FAIL", condition="preferred_label=FAIL"]

    build_ai_grouping -> polish
    polish -> done
}
